<br>
The groups should be set up like Simc said, this is always how we do it.  Puller, main assist, secondary assist, and slower all get their own clerics.  Usually on ROA raids we get 3 clerics so we stick the slower with either the cleric who has the puller (NOT the second assist) or with a druid and another shaman or something.<br>
<br>
If there are a couple tanks with low levels and/or bad resists, you need to find out who they are and stick them with the bards, and tell them to hide if it gets to be too bad healing them.  As guild leader I can really get on someone's case if I am their cleric and they're taking more AOE damage than they should.  I tell em they can't come back if they don't raise their fire/cold by at least a certain amount <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Usually Simc and I have the the puller and MA in our seperate groups.  Let's say I have the puller, Simc can just yell to me if she needs me to help out by putting remedy or divine light on the MA.  Nowadays on our HoT raids typicaly the only people that die are the puller, people who steal aggro from the MA, people who don't turn off for enrage (bleh this still happens) and people who don't hide from the AE when we tell them.  Oh and then there's the times we get so bored doing HoT for the 100th time and we are watching TV or goofing around or something and someone dies.  <br>
<br>
Another good thing to plan for is extra mobs.  If you have a mala/malo person there you should be able to handle multiple mobs.  You should plan for this by designating the secondary assist (you did put him with his own cleric didn't you?) and having a mental note who a possible 3rd assist will be.  The important thing on a multi pull is to make sure everyone stands up when you yell add, and make sure you /target the slower no matter what group you're in and make sure they stay alive until everything gets slowed.<br>
<br>
One time we were fighting a white wurm and it gated, and brough back THREE other mobs, a mix of raptors and wyverns I think (none aoe).  We had to finish off the white wurm and contain the adds.  Second assist tanked one and I had to yell at our shadow knight to HT the mob off the shaman who had just malo'd and slowed one.  Shaman ended up malo'ing and slowing the mob the SA was on and then finally got the last mob slowed and ended up tanking it himself by using torpor! (Yes Beomahn is the most amazing shaman I have ever met)<br>
<br>
Anyways HoT can be miserable if you do some things wrong but it can be a nice enjoyable farm once you get levels, resists, and a few strategies down.  On good HoT farm days in ROA we can get 18-20 people there, and when an AOE wurm we are fighting goes to enrage our monk is allready pulling ANOTHER AOE mob.<br>
